        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Creating a Shipment from Sales Order Lines",
            Slug = "shipments-creating-from-order-lines",
            Summary = "How the create-shipment dialog really works: pick the Sales Order first, then add lines from that order's open lines with quantity capped at what remains to ship — there is no free part picker.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 5,
            AppRoutes = """["/shipments"]""",
            Tags = """["shipments","shipping","create","sales-orders"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Creating a Shipment from Sales Order Lines\n\nIn QB Engineer a shipment is never assembled from a free part catalog. It is built **from the open lines of one Sales Order**, and every shipped quantity is capped at what is still owed on that line. This guarantees an order can never be over-shipped: the lines you can ship, and the most you can ship of each, come straight from the order.\n\n### Open the Create Dialog\n\nFrom the Shipments page (`/shipments`), click the **New Shipment** button in the page header. A wide dialog opens with a **split layout**:\n- **Main area (left):** the shipment's line items and the add-line form.\n- **Sidebar (right):** shipment details (Sales Order, carrier, tracking, weight, shipping cost) and notes.\n\n### Step 1 — Select the Sales Order First\n\nThe **Sales Order** autocomplete in the right sidebar is the only required header field, and it drives everything else. Start typing the order number, customer name, or customer PO and pick the match. Each option reads as `OrderNumber — CustomerName (CustomerPO)`.\n\nUntil you choose a Sales Order, the line area shows **\"Select an order first\"** — you literally cannot add a line without an order, because the lines come from the order.\n\n### Step 2 — Add Lines from the Order's Open Lines\n\nOnce a Sales Order is selected, the add-line form appears with an **Order Line** autocomplete. This dropdown lists only that order's lines that still have quantity left to ship — each entry shows the part/description and the remaining quantity. There is **no free part field**; you choose one of the order's lines.\n\nWhen you pick a line:\n- The **Quantity** field prefills with that line's remaining-to-ship amount.\n- The quantity is **capped** at the remaining amount. If you try to enter more than is left, the entry is rejected — you cannot ship 60 against a line that only has 50 left.\n- Quantity must be greater than 0. Fractional quantities are allowed (down to four decimal places) for parts sold in fractional units.\n\nClick **Add** to move the line into the line-items table above. Repeat for each order line you're fulfilling in this shipment. Each added line shows the part number, description, and quantity, with a red **X** to remove it.\n\nIf the order has nothing left to ship, the line area reads **\"All lines shipped\"** — there is nothing to put on a new shipment.\n\n### Step 3 — Optional Shipment Details\n\nIn the sidebar you may also enter, all optional at create time:\n- **Carrier** — free text (e.g., UPS, FedEx, Freight).\n- **Tracking Number** — if you already have one (manual carriers).\n- **Weight** and **Shipping Cost** — for record-keeping.\n- **Notes** — special handling or delivery instructions.\n\nNone of these block saving. They can also be set or corrected later from the shipment's detail view (see *Editing a Shipment, Ship-To, Rates & Labels*).\n\n### Step 4 — Save\n\nThe **Create Shipment** button stays disabled until two conditions are met: a Sales Order is selected **and** at least one line item has been added. If it's disabled, the validation icon next to it lists exactly what's missing. Click it to create the shipment — it starts in **Pending** status, and the page refreshes with the new shipment in the list.\n\n### Partial and Multiple Shipments\n\nBecause quantities are capped at the remaining amount per line, partial fulfillment is the natural model. Ship 50 of 100 now, and later create a second shipment against the same Sales Order for the remaining 50 — the order line's remaining quantity will have dropped to 50, and that's the most the second shipment will let you add. A single Sales Order can therefore have many shipments, each recording exactly which lines and quantities went out.\n\n### Common Pitfalls\n\n- **\"I can't find the part I want to ship.\"** You don't pick parts — you pick an *order line*. If the part isn't listed, it isn't on this Sales Order's open lines (either not ordered, or already fully shipped).\n- **\"It won't let me enter the quantity I want.\"** The quantity is capped at what remains to ship on that line. To ship more, the order line itself would need a higher quantity.\n- **\"The Add button is greyed out.\"** You haven't selected an order line, or the quantity is blank/zero/over the cap.\n- **\"Save is disabled.\"** You're missing the Sales Order, or you have no line items yet.","sections":[]}"""
        });

