            Tags = """["shipments","shipping","editing","rates","labels","carrier"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Editing a Shipment, Ship-To, Rates & Labels\n\nAfter a shipment is created, you complete it from its **detail view** — opened by clicking the shipment's row in the list. From there you correct details, choose a ship-to address, compare carrier rates, create a label, and finally mark it shipped. This article covers that post-create workflow.\n\n### Opening the Detail View\n\nOn the Shipments page, click any row. The detail view opens showing the shipment number, status chip, linked Sales Order, customer, carrier, tracking, dates, weight, cost, notes, line items, and an activity timeline. The available action buttons depend on the shipment's status.\n\n### Editing the Shipment\n\nWhile a shipment is still editable (any status except **Delivered** or **Cancelled**), an **Edit** (pencil) button appears in the detail header. It opens the Edit Shipment dialog, where you can set:\n\n- **Ship To (required)** — a dropdown of the customer's saved shipping addresses. Pick one, or choose **+ Add new address** to enter one inline.\n- **Tracking Number** — for manual carriers, or to correct a value.\n- **Shipping Cost** — a currency field.\n- **Weight** and **Dimensions** (Length / Width / Height) — used for carrier rating.\n- **Notes**.\n\nEvery edit is audited: the server writes a rollup activity-log entry on the shipment, visible in the detail view's activity timeline.\n\n#### Choosing or Creating a Ship-To Address\n\nThe Ship-To selector lists the customer's addresses of type *Shipping* or *Both*. If the customer has **no** saved shipping address, the dialog drops straight into the **add-new** form so you can't get stuck. When you choose **+ Add new address**, an inline address form appears:\n- **Address Label** (e.g., \"Dock 3\", \"Main plant\") and **Address Type** (Shipping or Both).\n- The full street address (line 1, optional line 2, city, state, postal code, country).\n- A **Set as default** toggle.\n\nOn save, the new address is created for the customer first, then attached to the shipment. A ship-to address is **required to get carrier rates** — so if rates come back empty, check that a ship-to is set.\n\n### Getting Carrier Rates\n\nWhen the shipment is in **Pending** or **Packed** status, a **Get Rates** button appears in the detail actions. It opens the Shipping Rates dialog, which requests rates from your configured carriers and lists each option with **carrier, service level, price, and estimated days**. Click a row to select it.\n\nRates need a ship-to address and (for meaningful results) weight/dimensions — set those via Edit first. If no rates return, the dialog shows an empty state; confirm the ship-to address and carrier configuration.\n\n### Creating a Label (API Carriers)\n\nWith a rate selected, click **Create Label**. For an integrated (API) carrier this purchases the label and, crucially, **assigns the tracking number** to the shipment automatically. The dialog then shows the label result — carrier, tracking number, and a **Download Ship Document** link. Close the dialog with **Done**.\n\n### Mark Shipped — and Why It's Sometimes Hidden\n\n**Mark Shipped** transitions the shipment to **Shipped** and records the shipped date (after a confirmation dialog). It's available from Pending or Packed.\n\nFor an **integrated (API) carrier**, shipping happens by *creating the label* — which is what assigns the tracking number. So Mark Shipped is intentionally **suppressed until a label/tracking number exists**; in its place you'll see a hint that a label is required. Create the label first, then Mark Shipped (or the act of labeling completes the ship step). For a **manual carrier** (no API), there's no label to buy, so Mark Shipped is available as soon as the shipment is Pending/Packed — you simply type the tracking number yourself.\n\n### Tracking the Shipment\n\nOnce a tracking number exists, a **Track** button appears. Click it to load the tracking timeline inline — each event with location, status, and timestamp — without leaving QB Engineer. A close button collapses the timeline.\n\n### The Ship Document (not a separate \"Packing Slip\")\n\nOnce a tracking number exists, the detail view exposes **Download Ship Document** and **Regenerate Ship Document**. The ship document is the combined, versioned PDF you print and include in the package — it wraps the carrier label with your company branding, a QR code, and a carrier badge (landscape), along with the shipment number, customer, ship-to address, and a table of line items and quantities.\n\n- **Download Ship Document** fetches the current version.\n- **Regenerate Ship Document** produces a fresh copy (e.g., after editing the address or lines) and confirms with a snackbar.\n\nBoth buttons appear **only after a tracking number exists**. There is no separate \"Packing Slip PDF\" button reachable from the shipment — the ship document is the printable artifact for the box.\n\n### Marking Delivered\n\nFrom **Shipped** or **In Transit**, a **Mark Delivered** button records the delivered date (after confirmation). Delivered is a terminal status — no further actions, and the shipment becomes read-only (no Edit).\n\n### Quick Sequence (API Carrier)\n\n1. Click the shipment row to open detail.\n2. **Edit** → set the **Ship-To** address (and weight/dimensions).\n3. **Get Rates** → select a service.\n4. **Create Label** → tracking number is assigned automatically.\n5. **Mark Shipped** (now available) → shipped date recorded.\n6. **Download Ship Document** → print and pack.\n7. Later: **Track**, then **Mark Delivered** on arrival.","sections":[]}"""
        });

