            AppRoutes = """["/shipments"]""",
            Tags = """["shipments","reference","advanced"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Shipments — Advanced Reference\n\nSide documentation for the ancillary corners of the Shipments module — features that exist on the API and detail screens but sit outside the core create/ship/track/deliver flow. Use it as a power-user lookup, not a tutorial.\n\n## Packages (CRUD on a shipment)\n\nA shipment can carry an explicit set of **packages** (boxes) under it, distinct from the shipment's single header `Weight`. Each package row has `trackingNumber`, `carrier`, `weight`, `length`, `width`, `height`, and a `status`. Packages are managed through their own endpoints:\n\n- `GET /api/v1/shipments/{id}/packages` — list packages.\n- `POST /api/v1/shipments/{id}/packages` — add a package (`AddShipmentPackageCommand`).\n- `PATCH /api/v1/shipments/{id}/packages/{packageId}` — update fields, including `status`.\n- `DELETE /api/v1/shipments/{id}/packages/{packageId}` — remove a package (soft-delete).\n\nThe `ShipmentService` exposes `getPackages`, `addPackage`, `updatePackage`, and `removePackage`. Packages matter downstream: **pickup scheduling** uses the package count and the summed package weight, and the **Bill of Lading** PDF includes the package list. When no packages exist, those features fall back to a count of `1` and the shipment header `Weight`.\n\n## Carrier Pickup Scheduling\n\nPickup is an API-carrier-only feature, surfaced server-side via:\n\n- `POST /api/v1/shipments/{id}/pickup` — `SchedulePickupCommand(ReadyTime?, CloseTime?, Instructions?)` → returns a `PickupConfirmation`.\n- `POST /api/v1/shipments/{id}/pickup/cancel` — cancels the scheduled pickup.\n\nScheduling rules enforced by `SchedulePickupHandler`:\n\n- The shipment must have an **assigned carrier** whose `IntegrationKind == Api` and that carries a non-empty `IntegrationServiceId`. A manual carrier returns \"arrange the pickup manually\"; no carrier returns \"assign one before scheduling a pickup.\"\n- A **default, active `CompanyLocation`** is required — it becomes the pickup origin address. Missing one blocks scheduling.\n- `ReadyTime` defaults to now; `CloseTime` defaults to ready + 8 hours; the validator requires `CloseTime` to be **after** `ReadyTime`.\n- Package count and weight come from the shipment's packages (or `1` / header `Weight` as fallback).\n- **One pickup at a time:** if `PickupConfirmationNumber` is already set, scheduling is rejected — cancel the existing pickup first. You cannot schedule a pickup for a **Cancelled** shipment.\n\nOn success the shipment stores `PickupConfirmationNumber` / `PickupScheduledDate` and logs a `pickup-scheduled` activity row. Pickup is **not wired into the current shipment UI service** — it is an API/integration capability today.\n\n## Packing Slip & Bill of Lading PDFs (generated elsewhere)\n\nTwo QuestPDF documents exist on the server but are **not exposed by buttons on the shipment detail screen** (which only surfaces the Ship Document):\n\n- `GET /api/v1/shipments/{id}/packing-slip` — `GeneratePackingSlipPdfQuery` → `PackingSlipPdfDocument`. Pulls the sales order, customer, ship-to `ShippingAddress`, and lines (with each line's Part).\n- `GET /api/v1/shipments/{id}/bill-of-lading` — `GenerateBillOfLadingPdfQuery` → `BillOfLadingPdfDocument`. Also includes `Packages`, and reads `company_name` / `company_address` / `company_phone` system settings for the carrier-facing header.\n\nBoth are reachable directly (API / other surfaces) but intentionally **not** part of the shipment screen's button set — the printable artifact the shipment screen offers is the combined **Ship Document**, not these. Treat packing slip and BOL as document endpoints, not in-screen actions.\n\n## Ship-To Address Validation\n\n`POST /api/v1/shipments/validate-address` (`ValidateShippingAddressCommand`) delegates to `IAddressValidationService` — USPS Address Information API (DPV confirmation + standardized address) when a USPS Web Tools User ID is configured, otherwise the format-only mock. The request requires `Street`, `City`, `State`, `Zip`, and `Country` (all non-empty); the response returns `IsValid`, a standardized address echo, and a `Messages` list. Validation is **advisory** — it standardizes/flags an address but does not by itself block a save.\n\n## Disabled / Missing Customer-Address Fallback\n\nThe Edit-Shipment ship-to selector is sourced from `GET /api/v1/shipments/{id}/customer-addresses` (the customer's addresses), then filtered client-side to types **`Shipping`** or **`Both`** — other address types are excluded from the dropdown. The fallback behavior:\n\n- If the customer has **no** Shipping/Both address, the dialog drops straight into the **`+ Add new address`** (`ADD_NEW`) inline form so you are never stuck without an option.\n- On the server, `UpdateShipment` guards that a chosen `ShippingAddressId` **belongs to this shipment's customer** — a mismatched address returns a clean **409** (\"does not belong to this shipment's customer\") rather than an FK 500, preventing shipping to another customer's address.\n\nNote `CustomerAddressResponseModel` exposes `IsDefault` but no active/disabled flag — \"disabled\" here means *not eligible for ship-to* (wrong type, or none available), handled by the type filter and the add-new fallback rather than a per-address enabled toggle.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        Log.Information("Seeded Shipments training modules");
